Cognitive Control of Multi-Appendage Robotic Extensions via Brain–Computer Interfaces

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

This work presents a complete mathematical and computational framework for real‑time control of two robotic hand extensions synchronized with human motor intent, enabling a human operator to effectively manipulate four independent hands (two biological, two robotic). The system integrates non‑invasive electroencephalography (EEG), Riemannian geometry for feature extraction, a hybrid CNN‑LSTM neural decoder, shared autonomy with an AI copilot, and intrinsic kinematic null space (IKNS) coordination. We formalize neural decoding as a supervised learning problem on the manifold of symmetric positive definite matrices, prove universal approximation for the decoder, derive stability conditions for multi‑body control under PID regulation, introduce a cognitive load‑aware adaptive blending mechanism, and specify a complete real‑time architecture with sub‑200 ms latency. The framework is validated through a proposed experimental protocol with concrete metrics: information transfer rate (bits/min), task completion time, NASA‑TLX workload, and robustness to signal‑to‑noise ratio degradation. This work provides a rigorous foundation for human augmentation in industrial, medical, and extraterrestrial environments.

Keywords: Brain–computer interface, multi‑appendage control, Riemannian geometry, hybrid deep learning, shared autonomy, supernumerary robotics.

---

1. Introduction

Human motor capability is inherently limited to two upper limbs. Extending this capability via robotic augmentation requires solving three fundamental problems: (1) neural intent extraction—decoding user intention from noisy brain signals; (2) intent‑to‑motion mapping—translating decoded intention into desired trajectories for multiple robotic hands; and (3) stable multi‑body control—coordinating biological and artificial limbs without interference or instability.

Recent advances in non‑invasive brain–computer interfaces (BCIs) have demonstrated feasibility for single‑limb prosthetic control [1,2]. However, existing systems focus on replacing a lost limb, not augmenting a healthy user with extra limbs. Extending to multi‑appendage control (e.g., two biological hands + two robotic hands) introduces new challenges: increased cognitive load, neural interference between limb representations, and the need for a coordination strategy that does not disrupt natural movement.

To address these challenges, this work proposes a unified mathematical and computational framework that integrates state‑of‑the‑art signal processing, deep learning, and robotic control. We adopt Riemannian geometry for EEG feature extraction, which respects the non‑Euclidean structure of covariance matrices and has been shown to improve classification robustness [3,4]. A hybrid CNN‑LSTM neural decoder is employed to capture both local spatiotemporal patterns and long‑term dependencies in motor imagery signals, with a universal approximation guarantee [5,6]. For coordination, we leverage the intrinsic kinematic null space (IKNS) concept [7,8], which allows supernumerary limbs to move without disturbing the user’s natural hand motion by exploiting the body’s inherent kinematic redundancy. To manage cognitive load, we introduce an adaptive shared autonomy mechanism where an AI copilot takes over low‑level tasks when user load exceeds a threshold, a strategy shown to reduce NASA‑TLX workload by over 20% in multi‑limb BCI settings [9,10]. The entire pipeline is designed for real‑time operation with end‑to‑end latency ≤ 200 ms, meeting the requirements for practical teleoperation and augmentation.

The main contributions of this paper are:

· A rigorous mathematical model of the closed‑loop BCI‑robotic system, including EEG as a stochastic process on a low‑dimensional manifold.
· A Riemannian geometry‑based feature extraction pipeline anchored in canonical references [3,4,11] and enhanced by recent advances in spatial filtering [12,13].
· A hybrid CNN‑LSTM neural decoder with a universal approximation proof and transfer learning for rapid calibration, grounded in real‑world hybrid deep learning studies [14–17].
· An intrinsic kinematic null space (IKNS) coordination law that decouples robotic from biological motion, following the formulation of Lisini Baldi et al. [7,8].
· A shared autonomy formalism with adaptive blending factor driven by a cognitive load model, supported by recent work on AI copilots for BCI [9,10,18].
· A complete real‑time architectural design with latency budget, hardware specifications, and validation metrics including information transfer rate [19].
· A proposed experimental protocol for evaluating the framework in single‑, dual‑, and four‑limb tasks.

This paper is organized as follows. Section 2 defines the system model and notation. Section 3 develops the neural signal processing pipeline using Riemannian geometry. Section 4 presents the decoding architecture and learning guarantees. Section 5 derives the multi‑appendage control laws, including IKNS coordination and PID stability. Section 6 introduces the cognitive load model and adaptive shared autonomy. Section 7 describes the real‑time implementation. Section 8 proposes experimental validation. Section 9 discusses limitations. Section 10 concludes.

Chapter 2: System Model and Notation

2.1 Preliminaries

We consider a human operator equipped with two biological hands and two robotic hand extensions. The overall system is a closed‑loop dynamical system comprising neural signal acquisition, feature extraction, intent decoding, robotic control, and sensory feedback.

Let t \in \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} denote continuous time. Discrete time indices are denoted by k with sampling period T_s = 4 ms (equivalent to 250 Hz), a standard rate for non‑invasive EEG acquisition.

Definition 2.1 (State variables).
Define the following vectors:

· \mathbf{x}(t) \in \mathbb{R}^{N_c} – raw EEG signals from N_c channels (typically 64–128).
· \mathbf{X}(t) \in \mathcal{X} \subset \mathbb{R}^d – feature vector extracted from the raw EEG.
· \mathbf{u}(t) \in \mathbb{R}^m – decoded motor intent (e.g., desired end‑effector velocities or joint angle velocities for the robotic hands).
· \mathbf{q}_h(t) \in \mathbb{R}^n – joint angles of the human’s two biological arms.
· \mathbf{q}_r(t) \in \mathbb{R}^m – joint angles of the two robotic hands. The total number of robotic degrees of freedom is m (e.g., 6 DOF per hand → m = 12).
· \boldsymbol{\tau}(t) \in \mathbb{R}^m – torque/force commands applied to the robotic joints.
· \mathbf{y}(t) \in \mathbb{R}^p – feedback signal (tactile, force, or proprioceptive) delivered to the user.

Assumption 2.1 (Separability of human and robotic dynamics).
The human’s biological limbs are under natural neuromuscular control and are not directly commanded by the BCI system. The robotic hands receive commands derived solely from the decoded intent \hat{\mathbf{u}}(t) and the feedback \mathbf{y}(t). There is no direct mechanical coupling between the human and robotic limbs; they operate in the same workspace but are kinematically independent.

2.2 Closed‑Loop Dynamics

The system operates as a cascade of five stages:

\underbrace{\mathbf{x}(t)}_{\text{EEG}} \;\xrightarrow{\text{Stage 1}}\; \mathbf{X}(t) \;\xrightarrow{\text{Stage 2}}\; \hat{\mathbf{u}}(t) \;\xrightarrow{\text{Stage 3}}\; \mathbf{q}_r^{\text{des}}(t) \;\xrightarrow{\text{Stage 4}}\; \boldsymbol{\tau}(t) \;\xrightarrow{\text{Stage 5}}\; \mathbf{y}(t)

where:

· Stage 1 (Acquisition & Preprocessing): \mathbf{x}(t) \mapsto \tilde{\mathbf{x}}(t) (filtering, artifact rejection).
· Stage 2 (Feature Extraction): \tilde{\mathbf{x}}(t) \mapsto \mathbf{X}(t) (Riemannian geometry).
· Stage 3 (Neural Decoding): \mathbf{X}(t) \mapsto \hat{\mathbf{u}}(t) (CNN‑LSTM).
· Stage 4 (Coordination & Control): \hat{\mathbf{u}}(t) \mapsto \mathbf{q}_r^{\text{des}}(t) \mapsto \boldsymbol{\tau}(t) (IKNS + PID).
· Stage 5 (Feedback Generation): \mathbf{q}_r(t) \mapsto \mathbf{y}(t) (tactile/force rendering).

Definition 2.2 (Closed‑loop system).
The complete system is described by the following equations:

\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{X}(t) &= \mathcal{F}(\{\mathbf{x}(s)\}_{s \le t}), \\
\hat{\mathbf{u}}(t) &= f_\theta(\mathbf{X}(t)), \\
\mathbf{q}_r^{\text{des}}(t) &= \mathcal{C}_{\text{IKNS}}(\hat{\mathbf{u}}(t), \mathbf{q}_h(t)), \\
\boldsymbol{\tau}(t) &= \mathcal{C}_{\text{PID}}(\mathbf{q}_r^{\text{des}}(t), \mathbf{q}_r(t)), \\
\mathbf{y}(t) &= \mathcal{H}(\mathbf{q}_r(t), \dot{\mathbf{q}}_r(t)),
\end{aligned}

where \mathcal{F} is the feature extraction functional, f_\theta is the neural decoder with parameters \theta, \mathcal{C}_{\text{IKNS}} is the IKNS coordination law, \mathcal{C}_{\text{PID}} is the low‑level PID controller, and \mathcal{H} is the feedback mapping.

2.3 Objective Function

The overall goal is to minimize the tracking error between the user’s intended motion and the actual robotic motion, while respecting cognitive and latency constraints. Define the instantaneous loss:

\ell(t) = \|\mathbf{q}_r(t) - \mathbf{q}_r^*(t)\|^2,

where \mathbf{q}_r^*(t) is the (unobservable) true desired trajectory as imagined by the user. Since \mathbf{q}_r^*(t) is not directly measurable, we use the decoded intent \hat{\mathbf{u}}(t) as a proxy. The long‑term objective is:

\mathcal{J}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}\left[ \int_0^\infty e^{-\lambda t} \|\mathbf{q}_r(t) - \mathbf{q}_r^{\text{des}}(t)\|^2 dt \right],

with \lambda > 0 a forgetting factor. The expectation is taken over the stochasticity of EEG signals, neural noise, and environmental disturbances.

