Chapter 3: Neural Signal Processing

3.1 EEG Signal Model

Assumption 3.1 (Additive noise model).
The raw EEG signal at channel i is modeled as:

x_i(t) = s_i(t) + n_i(t), \quad i = 1,\dots,N_c,

where s_i(t) is the latent neural source activity and n_i(t) is zero‑mean Gaussian noise with covariance \mathbb{E}[n_i(t) n_j(t+\tau)] = \sigma_n^2 \delta_{ij} \delta(\tau). In vector form:

\mathbf{x}(t) = \mathbf{s}(t) + \mathbf{n}(t), \quad \mathbf{x}(t) \in \mathbb{R}^{N_c}.

Assumption 3.2 (Low‑dimensional manifold).
The neural sources lie on a k-dimensional Riemannian submanifold of \mathbb{R}^{N_c} with k \ll N_c. Specifically, there exists a smooth embedding \phi: \mathbb{R}^k \to \mathbb{R}^{N_c} such that \mathbf{s}(t) = \phi(\mathbf{z}(t)) for some latent process \mathbf{z}(t).

3.2 Preprocessing

Before feature extraction, the raw EEG undergoes:

1. Bandpass filtering: A zero‑phase FIR filter with passband [0.5, 50] Hz to remove DC drift and high‑frequency noise.
2. Artifact rejection: Independent component analysis (ICA) to remove ocular, cardiac, and muscular artifacts. Let \mathbf{W} be the unmixing matrix. The cleaned signal is \tilde{\mathbf{x}}(t) = \mathbf{W}^{-1} \mathbf{W}_{\text{keep}} \mathbf{x}(t), where \mathbf{W}_{\text{keep}} selects only components corresponding to neural sources.

3.3 Covariance Matrix Estimation

For a time window of length L samples (e.g., L = 64 samples = 256 ms), define the centered data matrix:

\tilde{\mathbf{X}}_t = \left[ \tilde{\mathbf{x}}(t-L+1) - \boldsymbol{\mu}_t, \; \dots, \; \tilde{\mathbf{x}}(t) - \boldsymbol{\mu}_t \right] \in \mathbb{R}^{N_c \times L},

where \boldsymbol{\mu}_t = \frac{1}{L} \sum_{k=0}^{L-1} \tilde{\mathbf{x}}(t-k) is the local mean. The sample covariance matrix is:

\mathbf{C}(t) = \frac{1}{L-1} \tilde{\mathbf{X}}_t \tilde{\mathbf{X}}_t^\top \in \mathcal{P}(N_c),

where \mathcal{P}(N_c) denotes the set of N_c \times N_c symmetric positive definite matrices.

3.4 Riemannian Geometry of SPD Matrices

Definition 3.1 (Affine‑invariant Riemannian metric).
For any \mathbf{C} \in \mathcal{P}(N_c) and tangent vectors \boldsymbol{\xi}, \boldsymbol{\eta} \in T_{\mathbf{C}}\mathcal{P}(N_c) (symmetric matrices), the affine‑invariant metric is:

\langle \boldsymbol{\xi}, \boldsymbol{\eta} \rangle_{\mathbf{C}} = \operatorname{tr}\left( \mathbf{C}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\xi} \mathbf{C}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\eta} \right).

Proposition 3.1 (Riemannian distance).
The geodesic distance induced by the affine‑invariant metric is:

\delta_R(\mathbf{C}_1, \mathbf{C}_2) = \left\| \log\left( \mathbf{C}_1^{-1/2} \mathbf{C}_2 \mathbf{C}_1^{-1/2} \right) \right\|_F,

where \log is the matrix logarithm and \|\cdot\|_F is the Frobenius norm.

Proof. The affine‑invariant metric is invariant under congruence transformations: \langle \boldsymbol{\xi}, \boldsymbol{\eta} \rangle_{\mathbf{C}} = \langle \mathbf{A} \boldsymbol{\xi} \mathbf{A}^\top, \mathbf{A} \boldsymbol{\eta} \mathbf{A}^\top \rangle_{\mathbf{A} \mathbf{C} \mathbf{A}^\top} for any invertible \mathbf{A}. The geodesic from \mathbf{C}_1 to \mathbf{C}_2 is given by \gamma(t) = \mathbf{C}_1^{1/2} \exp\left( t \log(\mathbf{C}_1^{-1/2} \mathbf{C}_2 \mathbf{C}_1^{-1/2}) \right) \mathbf{C}_1^{1/2}. The length of this geodesic yields the stated distance. ∎

3.5 Tangent Space Projection

To use standard Euclidean classifiers, we project SPD matrices to the tangent space at a reference point \mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}}. A common choice is the Riemannian geometric mean (Karcher mean):

\mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}} = \arg\min_{\mathbf{C} \in \mathcal{P}(N_c)} \sum_{i=1}^N \delta_R^2(\mathbf{C}, \mathbf{C}_i),

computed iteratively. The logarithmic map at \mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}} is:

\log_{\mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}}}(\mathbf{C}) = \mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}}^{1/2} \log\left( \mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}}^{-1/2} \mathbf{C} \mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}}^{-1/2} \right) \mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}}^{1/2}.

The resulting tangent vector is a symmetric matrix. We vectorize it by extracting the upper triangular part with scaling:

\mathbf{X}(t) = \operatorname{vect}\left( \log_{\mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}}}(\mathbf{C}(t)) \right) \in \mathbb{R}^d, \quad d = \frac{N_c(N_c+1)}{2},

where for off‑diagonal entries (i,j) with i<j, we store \sqrt{2} times the element to preserve the inner product.

Proposition 3.2 (Local isometry).
The tangent space mapping \operatorname{vect} \circ \log_{\mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}}} is a local isometry: for any \mathbf{C}_1, \mathbf{C}_2 sufficiently close to \mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}},

\|\mathbf{X}_1 - \mathbf{X}_2\|_2 \approx \delta_R(\mathbf{C}_1, \mathbf{C}_2).

Proof. The logarithmic map is an isometry between a neighborhood of \mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}} and a neighborhood of 0 in the tangent space equipped with the Euclidean metric inherited from the Riemannian metric. The vectorization with off‑diagonal scaling preserves the Frobenius norm. ∎

3.6 Feature Normalization

Finally, each feature dimension is normalized to zero mean and unit variance over a running window to reduce non‑stationarity:

X_j(t) \leftarrow \frac{X_j(t) - \mu_j(t)}{\sigma_j(t) + \epsilon},

where \mu_j(t) and \sigma_j(t) are running estimates (e.g., exponential moving average) and \epsilon is a small constant.

