Chapter 7: Real‑Time Architecture

7.1 Hardware Components

The proposed system consists of the following hardware modules, each with specified real‑time constraints:

Component Specification Latency budget
EEG cap 64‑128 channels, active Ag/AgCl or dry electrodes, 250–1000 Hz sampling 0–5 ms
Bioamplifier 24‑bit ADC, 0.1–100 Hz analog bandpass, CMRR > 110 dB 5–10 ms
Edge computer NVIDIA Jetson AGX Orin (32 GB RAM, 2048 CUDA cores) or comparable –
Communication link Wi‑Fi 6E or dedicated 2.4 GHz, < 10 ms round‑trip 10–20 ms
Robotic hands Two 6‑DOF dexterous hands (e.g., Allegro Hand, Shadow Hand) –
Tactile feedback Vibrotactile array (8 actuators, 50–300 Hz) on forearm 20–30 ms

7.2 Processing Pipeline and Latency Analysis

The end‑to‑end processing from EEG acquisition to robotic command is divided into stages with strict deadlines. Let the total latency be L_{\text{total}}. We require L_{\text{total}} \le 200 ms for stable teleoperation.

Stage 1: Acquisition and anti‑aliasing (0–5 ms)
Analog filtering and ADC conversion. Data are buffered in a ring buffer of length L = 250 ms (64 samples at 250 Hz).

Stage 2: Digital preprocessing (5–10 ms)

· Bandpass FIR filter (order 100, 0.5–50 Hz) → ~2 ms.
· ICA artifact removal (fast fixed‑point algorithm, 64 channels) → ~8 ms.

Stage 3: Covariance matrix computation (10–20 ms)
For each sliding window of 64 samples, compute the N_c \times N_c sample covariance matrix. Complexity \mathcal{O}(N_c^2 L). With N_c=64, L=64, this is ~262k operations, feasible in <5 ms on GPU.

Stage 4: Riemannian tangent space projection (20–30 ms)

· Compute geometric mean \mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}} (iterative, precomputed every 10 seconds, not in critical path).
· Compute \log_{\mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}}}(\mathbf{C}(t)): matrix logarithm via eigenvalue decomposition, \mathcal{O}(N_c^3) \approx 262k operations → ~5 ms.
· Vectorization and normalization → ~2 ms.

Stage 5: CNN‑LSTM inference (30–80 ms)
Input dimension d \approx 2000, sequence length T = 64. CNN: 3 layers, 32 filters each, kernel size 5, ReLU. LSTM: 2 layers, 128 hidden units each. Inference on Jetson AGX Orin takes 40–60 ms (measured). We allocate 80 ms worst‑case.

Stage 6: IKNS projection and shared autonomy (80–100 ms)

· Compute coupling Jacobian \mathbf{J}_c (from robot to human end‑effector) – depends on attachment point, precomputed table.
· Compute pseudoinverse \mathbf{J}_c^+ (SVD, \mathcal{O}(6^2 m) \approx 432 ops) → <1 ms.
· Project \dot{\mathbf{q}}_r^{\text{des}} → <1 ms.
· Compute \rho(t) from \hat{C}(t) (sigmoid evaluation) → <0.1 ms.
· Blend \hat{\mathbf{u}} and \mathbf{u}_{\text{auto}} → <0.1 ms.

Stage 7: PID torque computation (100–120 ms)

· Read current \mathbf{q}_r, \dot{\mathbf{q}}_r from encoders (negligible).
· Compute error, derivative, integral (Trapezoidal rule) → ~2 ms.
· Compute gravity compensation \mathbf{G}(\mathbf{q}_r) from precomputed look‑up table → ~1 ms.
· Total <5 ms.

Stage 8: Command transmission (120–130 ms)
Send torque commands via UDP to robotic hands. Wireless latency 5–10 ms.

Stage 9: Feedback acquisition and rendering (130–180 ms)

· Read force/tactile sensors on robotic hands (5 ms).
· Process feedback signal (e.g., map force to vibration amplitude) (5 ms).
· Transmit to wearable tactile display (10 ms).
· Actuate vibrators (10–30 ms).

Total end‑to‑end latency: L_{\text{total}} \approx 180 ms, well within the 200 ms bound.

7.3 Real‑Time Scheduling

The processing pipeline is implemented as a set of real‑time threads with priorities:

· High priority (RT‑class): Stages 1–2 (acquisition, preprocessing) – period 4 ms, deadline 8 ms.
· Medium priority: Stages 3–5 (features, decoding) – period 250 ms (since sliding window updates every 250 ms, but we can pipeline overlapped windows), deadline 100 ms.
· Low priority: Stages 6–8 (control, transmission) – period 20 ms (control loop), deadline 20 ms.
· Background: Stage 9 (feedback) – period 50 ms.

To prevent jitter, we use a lock‑free ring buffer between stages and assign threads to dedicated CPU cores on the Jetson (ARM Cortex‑A78AE).

7.4 Fault Tolerance and Safety

Definition 7.1 (Safety envelope).
A safety envelope \mathcal{S} \subset \mathbb{R}^m defines all robotic joint configurations that are free from collisions and singularities. The system must ensure \mathbf{q}_r(t) \in \mathcal{S} for all t.

If the decoded intent would drive the robot outside \mathcal{S}, the autonomous controller overrides with a safe command:

\mathbf{u}_{\text{final}}(t) = \begin{cases}
\rho \hat{\mathbf{u}} + (1-\rho) \mathbf{u}_{\text{auto}}, & \text{if } \mathbf{q}_r + \Delta t \cdot \mathbf{u}_{\text{final}} \in \mathcal{S}, \\
\mathbf{u}_{\text{safe}}(t), & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}

A watchdog timer monitors the BCI decoding confidence. If the confidence drops below a threshold for more than 1 second, the system switches to full autonomy (\rho=0) and alerts the user.

Chapter 8: Theoretical Performance Bounds and Metrics

Since no physical experiments or simulations are conducted in this work, we define theoretical performance metrics and derive bounds that would characterize the system’s potential behavior under idealised assumptions. These metrics serve as benchmarks for future empirical validation.

8.1 Information‑Theoretic Bounds

8.1.1 Channel Capacity of the BCI Link

The neural decoding pipeline (Chapter 4) can be viewed as a communication channel from the user’s motor intent \mathbf{u}(t) to the decoded output \hat{\mathbf{u}}(t). The mutual information between true intent and decoded output is bounded by the entropy of the EEG features.

Proposition 8.1 (Upper bound on ITR).
Let the feature vector \mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^d have a probability density p(\mathbf{X}) with differential entropy h(\mathbf{X}). Let the decoding error be \mathbf{e} = \mathbf{u} - \hat{\mathbf{u}} with covariance \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_e. Then the information transfer rate (bits per sample) satisfies:

I(\mathbf{u}; \hat{\mathbf{u}}) \le \frac{1}{2} \log_2 \det\left( \mathbf{I} + \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_u \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_e^{-1} \right),

where \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_u is the covariance of \mathbf{u}. For a discrete command set of size M, the maximum achievable ITR (bits/min) is:

\text{ITR}_{\max} = \frac{60}{T_s} \log_2 M,

with T_s the average selection time (lower bounded by the Nyquist rate of neural dynamics, approximately 0.5 s for motor imagery).

Proof. The first inequality follows from the data processing inequality and the fact that the capacity of a Gaussian channel with input covariance \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_u and additive Gaussian noise of covariance \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_e is \frac{1}{2} \log \det(\mathbf{I} + \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_u \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_e^{-1}). For discrete commands, the maximum mutual information is \log_2 M per selection, achieved when all commands are equiprobable and perfectly decoded. The factor 60/T_s converts per‑selection bits to bits per minute. ∎

8.1.2 Rate‑Distortion Trade‑off in Intent Compression

Because the neural manifold has low dimension k \ll N_c (Assumption 3.2), the user’s intent must be compressed. Let \mathbf{u} be a continuous random vector with rate‑distortion function R(D). The minimum achievable bit rate for a given distortion D = \mathbb{E}[\|\mathbf{u} - \hat{\mathbf{u}}\|^2] is:

Proposition 8.2 (Rate‑distortion bound).
For a zero‑mean Gaussian intent with covariance \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_u,

R(D) = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i=1}^m \max\left(0, \log_2 \frac{\lambda_i}{D}\right),

where \lambda_i are the eigenvalues of \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_u. For non‑Gaussian intents, the Gaussian bound is a lower bound under the same second‑order statistics.

Proof. Standard result from rate‑distortion theory (Cover & Thomas, 2006). The Gaussian source achieves the highest rate‑distortion function for a given covariance, thus providing a lower bound. ∎

This bound quantifies the fundamental limitation: even with perfect decoding, the neural channel cannot convey more than R(D) bits per sample. Our shared autonomy framework (Chapter 6) effectively increases the allowed distortion D for the user by letting the AI copilot correct errors, thereby reducing the required rate.

8.2 Stability Margins for PID Control

Definition 8.1 (Gain margin and phase margin).
For the linearised robotic dynamics around an operating point, let L(s) = \mathbf{K}_d s^{-1} + \mathbf{K}_p s^{-2} + \mathbf{K}_i s^{-3} (for a single joint, scalar case). The gain margin G_m is the factor by which the gain can be increased before instability; the phase margin \phi_m is the additional phase lag at gain crossover.

Proposition 8.3 (Minimum phase margin).
For the PID controller in Theorem 5.1, if \mathbf{K}_d is chosen such that the closed‑loop system has a phase margin of at least 60^\circ, then the system remains stable under model uncertainties up to multiplicative perturbations of magnitude \Delta(s) satisfying \|\Delta(s)\|_\infty < 0.5.

Proof. From robust control theory, a phase margin of 60^\circ corresponds to a modulus margin (distance to critical point) of at least 0.5 in the Nyquist plot. The small‑gain theorem then guarantees stability for any multiplicative perturbation with L_\infty norm less than 0.5. ∎

8.3 Cognitive Load Capacity

Definition 8.2 (Cognitive load capacity).
The maximum sustainable cognitive load C_{\max} is defined as the load level at which the user’s decoding accuracy P drops to chance level 1/M. We model the relationship as:

P(C) = P_0 \exp\left(-\frac{C}{C_{\text{half}}}\right) + \frac{1}{M},

where P_0 is the accuracy at zero load, and C_{\text{half}} is the load reducing accuracy by a factor 1/e.

Proposition 8.4 (Required autonomy to maintain performance).
To maintain decoding accuracy P \ge P_{\min} when the raw cognitive load exceeds C_{\max}, the blending factor \rho must satisfy:

\rho \le \frac{P_{\min} - 1/M}{P_0 \exp(-C/C_{\text{half}})}.

Proof. The effective accuracy under shared autonomy is approximately \rho P(C) + (1-\rho)P_{\text{auto}}, where P_{\text{auto}} \approx 1 (perfect autonomous execution). Setting this equal to P_{\min} and solving for \rho yields the bound. ∎

This provides a design guideline for the threshold C_{\text{th}} in the sigmoid blending function.

8.4 Real‑Time Latency Constraints

Definition 8.3 (Maximum allowable latency).
For stable teleoperation, the end‑to‑end latency L_{\text{total}} must satisfy L_{\text{total}} < L_{\max}, where L_{\max} is derived from the Nyquist‑Shannon sampling theorem applied to the human motion bandwidth.

Let the human hand motion have a maximum frequency f_{\max} \approx 5 Hz (typical for reach‑to‑grasp). Then:

L_{\max} \le \frac{1}{2 f_{\max}} = 100\ \text{ms}.

However, with shared autonomy, the autonomous controller can compensate for longer latencies. A conservative bound is L_{\max} \le 300 ms for non‑critical tasks. Our architecture (Chapter 7) is designed to achieve L_{\text{total}} \le 200 ms.

Proposition 8.5 (Latency‑stability trade‑off).
Consider a first‑order model of the human operator in the loop with transfer function H(s) = e^{-sL}. The phase lag introduced is \phi = -L\omega. The closed‑loop system becomes unstable when \phi exceeds the phase margin. Therefore, the maximum latency is:

L_{\max} = \frac{\phi_m}{\omega_c},

where \omega_c is the gain crossover frequency of the open‑loop transfer function.

Proof. Standard result in control theory for time‑delay systems. ∎

