Chapter 9: Discussion

9.1 Summary of Theoretical Contributions

This work has developed a self‑contained mathematical framework for multi‑appendage BCI control. The key theoretical results are:

1. Riemannian geometry for EEG features (Chapter 3) provides a natural way to handle covariance matrices, with a proven local isometry (Proposition 3.2) that preserves discriminative information.
2. Universal approximation of hybrid CNN‑LSTM (Theorem 4.1) guarantees that, given sufficient data and network capacity, the decoder can approximate any continuous intent‑to‑feature mapping. This justifies the chosen architecture.
3. IKNS coordination (Proposition 5.1) gives an explicit projection that decouples robotic motion from biological hand motion, with a closed‑form solution using the Moore–Penrose pseudoinverse.
4. Global asymptotic stability of PID control (Theorem 5.1) is proven using a Lyapunov function that accounts for the full nonlinear robot dynamics, not just linearised approximations.
5. Input‑to‑state stability of shared autonomy (Theorem 6.1) shows that the adaptive blending mechanism does not destabilise the system, even in the presence of neural noise.
6. Performance bounds (Chapter 8) provide theoretical limits on information rate, latency, and cognitive load that any physical implementation must respect.

These results are purely mathematical and do not rely on any experimental data. They form a rigorous foundation for future engineering efforts.

9.2 Comparison with Existing Theoretical Work

The existing literature on BCI for single‑limb control has established many of the building blocks: Riemannian geometry [Barachant et al., 2012], CNN‑LSTM architectures [Kumar et al., 2025], and PID stability [Yarza et al., 2011]. However, the integration of these components into a coherent multi‑limb framework with shared autonomy and IKNS coordination is novel. Prior theoretical work on supernumerary limbs [Lisini Baldi et al., 2023] focused on kinematics but did not incorporate BCI decoding or cognitive load. Prior shared autonomy theory [Shanahan et al., 2025] assumed perfect intent estimation, whereas we explicitly model decoding errors and noise.

Thus, the main novelty lies in the combined mathematical model that spans neural signal processing, learning, control, and human factors, all expressed in a unified set of equations and proofs.

9.3 Limitations of the Theoretical Framework

Despite the rigorous derivations, several limitations remain:

1. Assumption of low‑dimensional manifold (Assumption 3.2) is plausible but not proven for multi‑limb motor imagery. The actual intrinsic dimension k may vary with task complexity. The framework does not provide a method to estimate k from data.
2. Gaussian noise assumption in the EEG model is a simplification. Real EEG noise is often non‑Gaussian and may exhibit long‑range dependence. The Riemannian approach is robust to some deviations, but the theoretical guarantees (e.g., optimality of the sample covariance) may not hold.
3. Linear projection in IKNS (Proposition 5.1) assumes a constant coupling Jacobian \mathbf{J}_c. In reality, the coupling between robotic and human motion depends on posture and muscle activation, which are nonlinear and time‑varying. The static projection is an approximation that may lead to residual interference.
4. PID stability proof assumes perfect knowledge of the robot dynamics and no unmodeled delays. In practice, communication latency and sensor noise can degrade performance. The robust stability margins derived in Section 8.2 provide some safety, but the system may still become unstable for large unmodeled dynamics.
5. Cognitive load model is heuristic; there is no universal mathematical definition of cognitive load. The specific weighted sum (Chapter 6) is one of many possibilities. The stability result (Theorem 6.1) relies on the autonomous controller being ISS, which may be difficult to verify for complex policies.
6. No validation – because no experiments or simulations are performed, the practical feasibility of achieving the theoretical bounds (e.g., ITR of 28 bits/min) remains unknown. The mathematical framework is necessary but not sufficient for real‑world deployment.

9.4 Open Theoretical Questions

Several mathematical questions remain unresolved and are left for future work:

· Optimal sensor placement: Given the low‑dimensional manifold assumption, what is the minimal number of EEG channels N_c needed to capture k degrees of intent? This is akin to a compressed sensing problem on the manifold.
· Convergence rate of the geometric mean: The Riemannian mean \mathbf{C}_{\text{ref}} is computed iteratively. What is the convergence rate as a function of the number of samples? This affects real‑time updates.
· Non‑linear IKNS: Can the linear projection be replaced by a nonlinear map that exactly cancels interference for all postures? This would require solving a partial differential equation for the null space foliation.
· Optimal blending function: The sigmoid \rho(C) is arbitrary. What is the optimal \rho(C) that minimises a cost function combining tracking error and cognitive load? This is a stochastic optimal control problem.
· Finite‑time convergence of the decoder: The universal approximation theorem is asymptotic; we lack bounds on the number of samples or network size required to achieve a given accuracy.

Addressing these questions would further strengthen the theoretical foundations.

