Appendix A: Mathematical Background

A.1 Linear Algebra and Matrix Calculus

Definition A.1 (Symmetric Positive Definite Matrix).
A matrix \mathbf{C} \in \mathbb{R}^{N \times N} is symmetric positive definite (SPD) if \mathbf{C} = \mathbf{C}^\top and \mathbf{x}^\top \mathbf{C} \mathbf{x} > 0 for all non‑zero \mathbf{x} \in \mathbb{R}^N. The set of all N \times N SPD matrices is denoted \mathcal{P}(N).

Proposition A.1 (Eigendecomposition of SPD).
Every \mathbf{C} \in \mathcal{P}(N) can be written as \mathbf{C} = \mathbf{U} \boldsymbol{\Lambda} \mathbf{U}^\top, where \mathbf{U} is orthogonal (\mathbf{U}^\top = \mathbf{U}^{-1}) and \boldsymbol{\Lambda} = \operatorname{diag}(\lambda_1, \dots, \lambda_N) with \lambda_i > 0. The matrix logarithm and exponential are defined as:

\log(\mathbf{C}) = \mathbf{U} \operatorname{diag}(\log \lambda_1, \dots, \log \lambda_N) \mathbf{U}^\top,

\exp(\mathbf{C}) = \mathbf{U} \operatorname{diag}(e^{\lambda_1}, \dots, e^{\lambda_N}) \mathbf{U}^\top.

Definition A.2 (Frobenius Norm).
For a matrix \mathbf{A} \in \mathbb{R}^{m \times n}, \|\mathbf{A}\|_F = \sqrt{\sum_{i,j} A_{ij}^2} = \sqrt{\operatorname{tr}(\mathbf{A}^\top \mathbf{A})}.

Definition A.3 (Moore–Penrose Pseudoinverse).
For \mathbf{A} \in \mathbb{R}^{m \times n}, the pseudoinverse \mathbf{A}^+ \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times m} satisfies \mathbf{A} \mathbf{A}^+ \mathbf{A} = \mathbf{A}, \mathbf{A}^+ \mathbf{A} \mathbf{A}^+ = \mathbf{A}^+, and \mathbf{A} \mathbf{A}^+ and \mathbf{A}^+ \mathbf{A} are symmetric. If \mathbf{A} has full column rank, \mathbf{A}^+ = (\mathbf{A}^\top \mathbf{A})^{-1} \mathbf{A}^\top.

A.2 Riemannian Geometry

Definition A.4 (Manifold, Tangent Space).
A differentiable manifold \mathcal{M} is a topological space locally homeomorphic to \mathbb{R}^d. For each point p \in \mathcal{M}, the tangent space T_p \mathcal{M} is the vector space of all tangent vectors at p.

Definition A.5 (Riemannian Metric).
A Riemannian metric assigns to each p \in \mathcal{M} an inner product \langle \cdot, \cdot \rangle_p on T_p \mathcal{M} that varies smoothly with p.

Definition A.6 (Geodesic Distance).
The geodesic distance \delta(p,q) between two points p,q \in \mathcal{M} is the infimum of the lengths of all smooth curves connecting p and q, where length is measured using the Riemannian metric.

Proposition A.2 (Affine‑Invariant Metric on \mathcal{P}(N)).
For \mathbf{C} \in \mathcal{P}(N) and \boldsymbol{\xi}, \boldsymbol{\eta} \in T_{\mathbf{C}}\mathcal{P}(N) (symmetric matrices), the affine‑invariant metric is:

\langle \boldsymbol{\xi}, \boldsymbol{\eta} \rangle_{\mathbf{C}} = \operatorname{tr}(\mathbf{C}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\xi} \mathbf{C}^{-1} \boldsymbol{\eta}).

This metric is invariant under congruence: \langle \mathbf{A} \boldsymbol{\xi} \mathbf{A}^\top, \mathbf{A} \boldsymbol{\eta} \mathbf{A}^\top \rangle_{\mathbf{A} \mathbf{C} \mathbf{A}^\top} = \langle \boldsymbol{\xi}, \boldsymbol{\eta} \rangle_{\mathbf{C}} for any invertible \mathbf{A}.

Proposition A.3 (Geodesic on \mathcal{P}(N)).
The geodesic from \mathbf{C}_1 to \mathbf{C}_2 under the affine‑invariant metric is:

\gamma(t) = \mathbf{C}_1^{1/2} \left( \mathbf{C}_1^{-1/2} \mathbf{C}_2 \mathbf{C}_1^{-1/2} \right)^t \mathbf{C}_1^{1/2}, \quad t \in [0,1].

The geodesic distance is \delta_R(\mathbf{C}_1, \mathbf{C}_2) = \|\log(\mathbf{C}_1^{-1/2} \mathbf{C}_2 \mathbf{C}_1^{-1/2})\|_F.

Proof. The curve \gamma(t) satisfies \gamma(0)=\mathbf{C}_1, \gamma(1)=\mathbf{C}_2, and its derivative \dot{\gamma}(t) = \gamma(t)^{1/2} \mathbf{S} \gamma(t)^{1/2} for some constant symmetric \mathbf{S}. The length is \int_0^1 \|\dot{\gamma}(t)\|_{\gamma(t)} dt = \|\mathbf{S}\|_F. Choosing \mathbf{S} = \log(\mathbf{C}_1^{-1/2} \mathbf{C}_2 \mathbf{C}_1^{-1/2}) minimises the length, yielding the formula. ∎

A.3 Stability Theory

Definition A.7 (Lyapunov Function).
For a dynamical system \dot{\mathbf{z}} = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{z}), a Lyapunov function is a continuously differentiable function V(\mathbf{z}) such that V(\mathbf{z}) > 0 for \mathbf{z} \neq \mathbf{0}, V(\mathbf{0}) = 0, and \dot{V}(\mathbf{z}) = \nabla V \cdot \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{z}) \le 0 (or <0 for asymptotic stability).

Theorem A.1 (LaSalle’s Invariance Principle).
If V is a Lyapunov function on a compact set \Omega and \dot{V}(\mathbf{z}) \le 0 in \Omega, then every trajectory starting in \Omega approaches the largest invariant set contained in \{\mathbf{z} \in \Omega : \dot{V}(\mathbf{z}) = 0\} as t \to \infty.

A.4 Universal Approximation Theorems

Theorem A.2 (Cybenko, 1989 – Single Hidden Layer).
Let \sigma be a continuous non‑constant bounded function. Then the set of functions of the form \sum_{i=1}^N \alpha_i \sigma(\mathbf{w}_i^\top \mathbf{x} + b_i) is dense in C([0,1]^d).

Theorem A.3 (Zhou, 2020 – Convolutional Networks).
Convolutional neural networks with sufficiently many filters and layers can approximate any continuous function on a compact set to arbitrary accuracy, provided the activation function is non‑polynomial.

Theorem A.4 (Siegelmann & Sontag, 1995 – RNNs).
Recurrent neural networks (including LSTMs) with rational weights are Turing complete, hence can approximate any dynamical system to arbitrary precision.

